  "prompt": "What three books should an economics undergraduate read?",
  "response": "If you're studying economics as an undergraduate, it's valuable to gain different perspectives and insights that go beyond standard textbooks. Here are three highly recommended books that can deepen your understanding of economics:\n\n1. **\"Freakonomics: A Rogue Economist Explores the Hidden Side of Everything\" by Steven D. Levitt and Stephen J. Dubner**  \n   This book takes an unconventional approach to economics by applying economic theory to a wide range of real-world issues. It demonstrates how economic principles can be used to understand incentives and behavior in unexpected areas of everyday life. It's accessible and engaging, making complex concepts easier to grasp.\n\n2. **\"The Wealth of Nations\" by Adam Smith**  \n   As a foundational text in the field of economics, this classic work provides a comprehensive insight into economic principles that have influenced economic thought for centuries. Smith discusses concepts like the division of labor, free markets, and the invisible hand, which are fundamental to economic theory.\n\n3. **\"Capital in the Twenty-First Century\" by Thomas Piketty**  \n   This modern classic delves into wealth and income inequality in the modern world. Piketty combines historical analysis and data to examine how wealth distribution has evolved and presents arguments for addressing inequality. It offers a thorough examination of how economic systems impact society, making it a crucial read for understanding contemporary economic issues.\n\nThese books will help you develop a broader understanding of economic theories and how they apply to real-world scenarios, equipping you with diverse perspectives in your studies.",
